	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Toktuk Wartalon</b><br /><i>No way to turn it off. It's that way for a reason.<br />
<br />
I will say that it's forced groups I've been in to get rid of bad players, though. In EQ1, there was a tendancy to let bad players tag along and just watch them die every so often. In EQ2, I find that my groups will quickly replace a bad player if they come across one.<br />
<br />
Example: The other night we had a guy who would stop responding every so often. His character would stop moving, no spell casting, nothing. And when he was around, he would pull mobs nearby, regardless of whether we were currently taking on an encounter or not. He finally said that he was getting up and playing with his cat every so often because, "it looked so cute." We talked him into giving someone else group leadership and kicked him out. He followed us around yelling for awhile, but no one responded to him and we picked up someone else to fill his spot. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /><br />
<br />
-Tok</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Sorry but thats just a horrible story.<br />
<br />
Mind you, i understand why it went down like that, but its horrible cause you were forced to do it. I wouldnt want someone in my group that was potentialy going cause us all exp lose. I have to say this is the first thing in EQ2 i have heard of that really made me step back and go ... omg thats bull****.<br />
<br />
Ill take durability deaths all day over that heh.</p>
	
	
	
